# Summary

The Unihiker is a new single-board computer from RFRobot. It offers a number of features that make it a great choice for robotics projects, including a 2.8-inch touchscreen display, Wi-Fi and Bluetooth. It is equipped with light sensor, accelerometer, gyroscope and microphone. With built-in co-processor, it is able to communicate with various analog/digital/I2C/UART/SPI sensors and actuators.

DFRobot have kindly sent a Unihiker to the Maker Forge for testing and review. This article will cover the unboxing and initial impressions of the device.

# Features

- 2.8-inch touchscreen
- Easy setup via Type-C cable and programming through a browser
- Rich interfaces for controlling open-source hardware
- Direct control of hundreds of sensors and actuators using Python
- Integrated local IoT services that can stores data locally
- Built-in Wi-Fi and Bluetooth for wireless connectivity
- Supports popular coding software like Jupyter notebook, VS Code, VIM, Mind+

See the full specification here: [Unihiker Specification](https://www.unihiker.com/wiki/specification)

# Form factor

The Unihiker is a small device comparable in size to the Raspberry Pi and other single board computers (SBCs), however the layout is entirely different.

![Unihiker](https://dfimg.dfrobot.com/64228321aa9508d63a42c28b/wiki/9093b27717d6a448aa0fed0c2e68fd23.png)
_Image credit: [DFRobot](https://www.unihiker.com/wiki/board-overview)_

It has a 2.8-inch touchscreen display and a number of ports for connecting sensors and actuators. The 40 pin GPIO is instead a selection of 3 pin or 4 pin JST(?) connectors with various functions. There is also an edge connector.

